{"award_age":58.0,"bio_image":null,"category":"Chemistry","country":"United Kingdom","date_of_birth":"1917-09-07T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2013-12-08T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":[],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Cornforth","mini_bio":"<p><b>Sir John Warcup \"Kappa\" Cornforth, Jr.<\/b>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-NNDB_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Cornforth#cite_note-NNDB-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Companion_of_the_Order_of_Australia\" title=\"Companion of the Order of Australia\" class=\"mw-redirect\">AC<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Commander_of_the_Order_of_the_British_Empire\" title=\"Commander of the Order of the British Empire\" class=\"mw-redirect\">CBE<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fellow_of_the_Royal_Society\" title=\"Fellow of the Royal Society\" class=\"mw-redirect\">FRS<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Australian_Academy_of_Science#Fellows\" title=\"Australian Academy of Science\">FAA<\/a> (7 September 1917 \u2013 8 December 2013), was an Australian\u2013<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_Kingdom\" title=\"United Kingdom\">British<\/a> chemist who won the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Chemistry\">Nobel Prize in Chemistry<\/a> in 1975 for his work on the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Stereochemistry\" title=\"Stereochemistry\">stereochemistry<\/a> of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Enzyme\" title=\"Enzyme\">enzyme<\/a>-catalysed reactions,<sup id=\"cite_ref-nature_obit_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Cornforth#cite_note-nature_obit-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-EB_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Cornforth#cite_note-EB-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> becoming the only Nobel laureate born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/New_South_Wales\" title=\"New South Wales\">New South Wales<\/a>.<\/p><p>Cornforth investigated enzymes that catalyse changes in organic compounds, the substrates, by taking the place of hydrogen atoms in a substrate's chains and rings. In his syntheses and descriptions of the structure of various <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Terpene\" title=\"Terpene\">terpenes<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Olefin\" title=\"Olefin\" class=\"mw-redirect\">olefins<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Steroid\" title=\"Steroid\">steroids<\/a>, Cornforth determined specifically which cluster of hydrogen atoms in a substrate were replaced by an enzyme to effect a given change in the substrate, allowing him to detail the biosynthesis of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cholesterol\" title=\"Cholesterol\">cholesterol<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Cornforth#cite_note-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> For this work, he won a share of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1975, alongside co-recipient <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vladimir_Prelog\" title=\"Vladimir Prelog\">Vladimir Prelog<\/a>, and was knighted in 1977.<sup id=\"cite_ref-RIAUS_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Cornforth#cite_note-RIAUS-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"John Cornforth","place_of_birth":"Sydney ,  Australia","place_of_death":"England","text":"John Cornforth ,  born in Australia , Chemistry, 1975","year":1975.0}